## About the Project

The SacOverflow development team, consisting of Computer Science undergraduates from California State University, Sacramento, is behind this project.

This project is aimed at assisting Project Managers in managing their team and projects. By making use of this software, supervisors or relevant stakeholders will be allowed to make more informed decisions within their organization and simplify their day-to-day task duties. This software is to be developed with the intention of being used on both mobile and web-based platforms.

## Getting Started

To start local development and launch the application, please follow the following steps:
### Prerequisites

 1. Download and **install NodeJS** for your appropriate machine
    - [![NodeJS Icon][nodejs-icon]](https://nodejs.org/en/)
		 - Ensure this is Version 20.
	 - For installation guidance, refer to the YouTube guides below:
		 - [Youtube Guide Mac](https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=nodejs+installation+mac+guide)
		 - [Youtube Guide Windows](https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=nodejs+installation+windows+guide)
	 2. Verify **Node Package Manager (NPM) installation**. 
	    - [![NPM Icon][npm-icon]](https://www.npmjs.com/)
		 - NPM typically comes with the NodeJS installation.
		     - [NPM Download and Installation Guide](https://docs.npmjs.com/downloading-and-installing-node-js-and-npm)
	 3. **Install Git** to your local machine additionally
		 - [Git SCM Installation Guide](https://git-scm.com/book/en/v2/Getting-Started-Installing-Git)
	 4. Check and verify installations
		 - You can verify the installations have indeed been installed by running the 3 following commands
		 - To confirm that both NodeJS and NPM are correctly installed, run the following two commands in your terminal
		 ![](data:image/png;base64,)
	![](data:image/png;base64,)			
    These commands will display the versions of NodeJS, NPM & git which are installed on the respective machine & confirm the installation.
### Installation
**1. Clone the Repository**
![](data:image/png;base64,)
An additional step which can be taken if Visual Studio Code has been installed, is to simply run within the same terminal code . to open up the code base directly in Virtual Studio Code.


**2. Install Dependencies**
 ![](data:image/png;base64,)
 
**3. Setup Configuration**
	 - Create a file title .env.local in the root directory of the CAMEL-Services directory. With the same terminal shell open, run the following command for your respective machine.
![Mac Setup](data:image/png;base64,)
		- Verify the file .env.local is listed in the same directory after running the verification command.
![Windows Setup](data:image/png;base64,)
		- Verify on your Windows machine that the file is listed in the same directory
		- Populate the `.env.local` file with the following environment variables. Such values should never be shared publicly and need to be retrieved from the Supabase dashboard.
    - Retrieve environment and secret keys from the development team. 
	
```bash
NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL= {DASHBOARD_VALUE}
NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY= {DASHBOARD_VALUE}
SUPABASE_SERVICE_KEY={DASHBOARD_VALUE}
```


**4. Run the development server.** 
![](data:image/png;base64,)

### Features

-   User Authentication (Login/Sign Up)
-   Business Dashboard (Overview of finances and projects)
-   Project Dashboard (Overview of project details and tasks)

## Getting Started

First, run the development server:

```bash
npm run dev
# or
yarn dev
# or
pnpm dev
# or
bun dev
```

Open [http://localhost:3000](http://localhost:3000) with your browser to see the result.
